Here's the full migration analysis and replacement code.

## Pattern Classification

| Location | API | Pattern | Replacement |
|---|---|---|---|
| `RunLoop()` | `while (true)` | Cancellable work loop | `CancellationToken` loop check |
| `RunLoop()` | `WaitOne()` | Blocking call interruption | `WaitHandle.WaitAny` with `token.WaitHandle` |
| `Stop()` | `Thread.Interrupt()` | Blocking call interruption | `cts.Cancel()` |
| `Stop()` | `Thread.Abort()` | Timeout enforcement / forced kill | `cts.Cancel()` (cooperative) |

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly ManualResetEvent _newEvent = new(false);
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new();
    private readonly object _lock = new();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Thread? _thread;

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var token = _cts.Token;
        var handles = new WaitHandle[] { _newEvent, token.WaitHandle };

        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // WaitAny unblocks on either a new event OR cancellation
            int index = WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles);
            if (index == 1) // token.WaitHandle was signaled
                break;

            _newEvent.Reset();

            string? item = null;
            lock (_lock)
            {
                if (_queue.Count > 0)
                    item = _queue.Dequeue();
            }

            if (item is not null)
                Handle(item);
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();           // signals token.WaitHandle → unblocks WaitAny
        _thread?.Join(5000);     // wait up to 5s for clean exit
        // No Thread.Abort fallback — cooperative cancellation guarantees exit
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _newEvent.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## What Changed and Why

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `while (true)` | `while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)` | Loop must cooperatively check for cancellation |
| `_newEvent.WaitOne()` | `WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles)` | Allows **both** new-event and cancellation to unblock the wait |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | `Interrupt` is obsolete (`SYSLIB0046`); the cancel signal unblocks `WaitAny` via `token.WaitHandle` |
| `Thread.Abort()` | *(removed)* | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+ (`SYSLIB0006`); cooperative exit makes it unnecessary |
| No `IDisposable` | `IDisposable` added | `CancellationTokenSource` and `ManualResetEvent` are `IDisposable` — leaking them causes timer/callback leaks |

## Key Pitfalls to Watch For

1. **`WaitOne` → `WaitAny` is critical.** If you only replace the loop condition but keep `_newEvent.WaitOne()`, the thread stays blocked indefinitely because `IsCancellationRequested` is never re-checked until a new event arrives.

2. **Cancellation is not immediate.** If `Handle(item)` runs long-running work, `Stop()` won't return until that call finishes. If that's a concern, pass `_cts.Token` into `Handle()` and check it at regular checkpoints.

3. **Don't catch and swallow `OperationCanceledException`.** If you convert to `async`/`Task.Run` later, let `OCE` propagate to the caller.

4. **The original code has a pre-existing bug**: multiple `Enqueue` calls between loop iterations can race — `Set()` is called multiple times but `Reset()` clears the signal before draining all items. The migrated code preserves this behavior, but if you want correctness, drain the entire queue per wakeup:

```csharp
// Drain all queued items per wakeup
while (true)
{
    string? item;
    lock (_lock)
    {
        if (_queue.Count == 0) break;
        item = _queue.Dequeue();
    }
    Handle(item);
}
```

## Modern Alternative: `Channel<T>`

For new .NET 8 code, consider `Channel<T>` which replaces the manual event + lock + queue entirely:

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Task? _runTask;

    public void Start() =>
        _runTask = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken token)
    {
        await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(token))
            Handle(item);
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item) =>
        _channel.Writer.TryWrite(item);

    public void Stop()
    {
        _channel.Writer.Complete();  // signal no more items
        _cts.Cancel();               // break out of waiting reads
        _runTask?.Wait(5000);
    }

    public void Dispose() { Stop(); _cts.Dispose(); }
}
```

This eliminates the `ManualResetEvent`, `lock`, `Queue`, and `Thread` entirely — and fixes the multi-enqueue drain bug for free.
